using C functions: sprintf, vsprintf, snprintf, vsnprintf

## guideline
1. The number of format specifiers in the format string must match the number of arguments to avoid format string vulnerabilities.
2. Prefer using length-parameterized formatting functions (e.g., snprintf) and correctly pass the buffer capacity, rather than sprintf / vsprintf. sprintf / vsprintf cannot limit output length; they should only be used in special cases where it is absolutely necessary, and even then, you must ensure the formatted string length (including '\0') is less than the destination buffer size and boundary checks have been performed.
3. When using snprintf, always check the return value to ensure output was not truncated. If the return value is greater than or equal to the buffer size, output was truncated and must be handled appropriately.

